You can create a table with specified row lengths and sequences of integers by using LaTeX's `tabular` environment. Here's an example code that creates a table with rows having a specific number of cells, where each cell contains a sequence of integers repeated the same number of times as the row number, starting with 1 and continuing until the specified number of rows is reached:
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{array}

\begin{document}

\newcounter{rowcounter}
\setcounter{rowcounter}{1}

\begin{table}[h]
    \centering
    \caption{Sequence of integers in a table}
    \renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.5}
    \begin{tabular}{c|*{5}{c}}
        \hline
           & \multicolumn{5}{c}{Row \therowcounter} \\
        \hline
        & \textbullet & \textbullet & \textbullet & \textbullet & \textbullet \\
        \hline
        1 & 1 & 2 & 3 & 4 & 5 \\
        \hline
        2 & 6 & 7 & 8 & 9 & 10 \\
        \hline
